Text.Value: You're right. Her temper will get the better of her.
She's been through a lot. Give her time.
It's not a problem most of us have.
I'm going to help her in the fight against Lorroakan.
Aylin left to face that wizard - Lorroakan, was it?
It all feels like recklessness to me.
She's reckless but powerful. Lorroakan is probably already dead.
Thank you for fighting by her side. It means more to her - to me - than you know.
Even after all she's been through, she thinks herself unstoppable - invincible.
I hope you're right. He sounds like a vile, vile man. I'd have liked to get a few licks in myself, honestly.
I noticed she seemed a little unlike herself by the battle's end.
Aylin seems a little subdued since you came back. Did something happen?
She has. But 'time' means something different to Aylin than you or I. She once went for a walk and didn't come back for a month. Couldn't understand why I was upset, either.

EditorData.NodeContext: She is worried, but she says this with humour, too. She understands Aylin.

Text.Value: Lorroakan can't harm her. Have faith.
My poor darling. She's singular among us all.
I'll rest a little easier if you do. You fought well against my father. I imagine a rat like Lorroakan will be nothing in comparison.
Leave.
I suppose she's tired of power-hungry mages trying to steal her immortality.
She can take care of herself. She's Dame Aylin, remember?
I wanted to help her, but she said she fights better when she knows I'm safe. I understand, I suppose - I feel the same about her.
You should've seen her before... before everything. When she'd step off the battlefield, oh how she glowed. Literally.
But the years - the decades, the century - have taken their toll. She's seen more hurt than we can dream of.
Moonmaiden, hear me: protect the woman we both love so very dearly...
I've never known Aylin to slow down. Particularly not after a battle.
She needs cherishing, now. And I'm up for the task.
She certainly is. And she always will be, won't she? Gods, I miss her already.
He can harm her. Just as Ketheric did. She'll survive it, but she can suffer like any of us - and for longer.
The usual mayhem. Maybe she's just tired.
That's my greatest fear.

Synopsis: Camp dialog with Isobel in which she expresses her frustration and anxiety while waiting for nightsong after she left to kill Lorroakan.
